From 70430fe38454dd65618569287e53286d1ae8a663 Mon Sep 17 00:00:00 2001
From: Arecsu <alejandro9r@gmail.com>
Date: Mon, 4 May 2026 22:14:57 -0300
Subject: [PATCH 1/2] winewayland: snap CSD maximized windows to monitor work
 area

When a wayland configure event sets the maximized state on a window
that uses client-side decorations (the compositor is not drawing the
title bar / borders for us), Wine's WM_GETMINMAXINFO computes the
window placement with a negative WS_THICKFRAME inset on the top-left,
inherited from the Windows server-side-decoration convention where
the OS hides the resize border underneath the screen edge. With CSD
there is no such border to hide, so that inset is dead space that
visibly shifts the window's drawn content past the maximized work
area and produces a small gap on the top and left edges.

Override the position in the wayland driver's configure handler:
when transitioning to or staying in maximized state on a CSD window,
snap the window's top-left to the monitor's work-area origin instead
of inheriting the inset position Wine has already committed. The size
already comes from the compositor's configure (work-area sized) so
the resulting rect fills the work area exactly.

Note: a transient blur of the canvas may still be visible during a
fast maximize \xe2\x86\x92 shrink \xe2\x86\x92 maximize cycle. That is the host Vulkan
WSI / DXVK swapchain not yet matching the new wayland surface size,
which the compositor compensates for by stretching the previous frame
until DXVK presents a new swapchain at the new size; it is outside the
scope of this fix.
---
 dlls/winewayland.drv/window.c | 22 +++++++++++++++++++++-
 1 file changed, 21 insertions(+), 1 deletion(-)

diff --git a/dlls/winewayland.drv/window.c b/dlls/winewayland.drv/window.c
index b78498a4bd5b..65d1b71dd1ff 100644
--- a/dlls/winewayland.drv/window.c
+++ b/dlls/winewayland.drv/window.c
@@ -733,7 +733,27 @@ static void wayland_configure_window(HWND hwnd)
     }
 
     SetRect(&rect, 0, 0, window_width, window_height);
-    OffsetRect(&rect, data->rects.window.left, data->rects.window.top);
+    /* For maximized windows under client-side decorations we override the
+     * default position. Win32's WM_GETMINMAXINFO returns ptMaxPosition with
+     * a negative WS_THICKFRAME inset (so the resize border falls under the
+     * screen edge — a Windows SSD convention), and Wine has already moved
+     * the window there by the time the configure arrives. With CSD there is
+     * no actual border to hide, so that inset is dead space that visibly
+     * shifts the window's drawn content past the maximized work area. Snap
+     * the maximized window to the monitor work-area origin instead. */
+    if ((state & WAYLAND_SURFACE_CONFIG_STATE_MAXIMIZED) &&
+        surface->processing.decor != ZXDG_TOPLEVEL_DECORATION_V1_MODE_SERVER_SIDE)
+    {
+        HMONITOR mon = NtUserMonitorFromWindow(hwnd, MONITOR_DEFAULTTOPRIMARY);
+        MONITORINFO mi = {.cbSize = sizeof(mi)};
+        if (mon && NtUserGetMonitorInfo(mon, &mi))
+        {
+            OffsetRect(&rect, mi.rcWork.left, mi.rcWork.top);
+            flags &= ~SWP_NOMOVE;
+        }
+        else OffsetRect(&rect, data->rects.window.left, data->rects.window.top);
+    }
+    else OffsetRect(&rect, data->rects.window.left, data->rects.window.top);
 
     wayland_win_data_release(data);
 
